a   (ID)
  • article   (follow the link for more info)
    • The earthquake caused a tsunami.   [AMR 1.2 generally does not represent articles.]     (cause-01 :ARG0 earthquake :ARG1 tsunami)    Example

             
      Example: The earthquake caused a tsunami. [isi_0002.378]
      (c / cause-01
           :ARG0 (e / earthquake)
           :ARG1 (t / tsunami))

      (b / background
           :li "a")
  • :mod   (ID)
    • Group A: (1) Germany (2) Brazil (3) Italy (4) Argentina     (group :mod "A")    Example

             
      Example: Group A: (1) Germany (2) Brazil (3) Italy (4) Argentina [isi_0002.115]
      (c / consist-01
           :ARG1 (g / group
                :mod "A")
           :ARG2 (a2 / and
                :op1 (c2 / country
                     :wiki "Germany"
                     :li 1
                     :name (n / name
                          :op1 "Germany"))
                :op2 (c3 / country
                     :wiki "Brazil"
                     :li 2
                     :name (n2 / name
                          :op1 "Brazil"))
                :op3 (c4 / country
                     :wiki "Italy"
                     :li 3
                     :name (n3 / name
                          :op1 "Italy"))
                :op4 (c5 / country
                     :wiki "Argentina"
                     :li 4
                     :name (n4 / name
                          :op1 "Argentina"))))
    • Figure 6a     (figure :mod "6a")    Example

  • string-entity   (ID)   (string of characters incl. letters, words, phrases, symbols)
    • The adulteress was required to wear a scarlet "A" on her dress.     (wear-01 :ARG1 (string-entity :value "A") :location dress)    Example

             
      Example: The adulteress was required to wear a scarlet "A" on her dress. [isi_0002.703]
      (r / require-01
           :ARG1 (w / wear-01
                :ARG0 (w2 / woman
                     :ARG0-of (c / commit-02
                          :ARG1 (a / adultery)))
                :ARG1 (s2 / string-entity
                     :value "A"
                     :mod (s / scarlet))
                :location (d / dress
                     :poss w2)))
    • In English, "a" is a very common word.     (word :mod common :domain (string-entity :value "a"))    Example

      (w / word

                     :op1 "English")))

abbreviation   (ID)
  • Abbreviations are generally expanded.
    • The CEO of Oshkosh Corp. talked about IEDs on TV.     (talk-01 :ARG0 (officer :mod chief :mod executive) :ARG1 (device ...) :medium television)    Example

             
      Example: The CEO of Oshkosh Corp. talked about IEDs on TV. [isi_0002.688]
      (t / talk-01
           :ARG0 (p / person
                :ARG0-of (h / have-org-role-91
                     :ARG1 (c / company
                          :wiki "Oshkosh_Corporation"
                          :name (n / name
                               :op1 "Oshkosh"
                               :op2 "Corp."))
                     :ARG2 (o / officer
                          :mod (c2 / chief)
                          :mod (e2 / executive))))
           :ARG1 (d / device
                :ARG1-of (i / improvise-01)
                :ARG1-of (e / explode-01
                     :ARG1-of (p2 / possible-01)))
           :medium (t2 / television))
    • IDK if he's str8.     (know-01 :polarity - :ARG0 i :ARG1 (truth-value :polarity-of (straight-05 :ARG1 he)))    Example

             
      Example: IDK if he's str8. [isi_0002.691]
      (k / know-01

  • Exception: In proper names, abbreviations are not expanded.   (Common names are canonicalized by their wikification.)
    • western countries (e.g. the UK, the USA and France)     (and :op1 (country :wiki "United_Kingdom" :name (name :op1 "UK")) :op2 (country :wiki "United_States" :name (name :op1 "USA")))    Example

      (c / country
           :location (w / world-region
                :wiki "Western_world"
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "West"))

                :op1 (c2 / country
                     :wiki "United_Kingdom"
                     :name (n2 / name
                          :op1 "UK"))
                :op2 (c3 / country
                     :wiki "United_States"
                     :name (n3 / name
                          :op1 "USA"))
                :op3 (c4 / country
                     :wiki "France"
                     :name (n4 / name
                          :op1 "France"))))
    • USC Prof. Z. Meyer lives in LA, Calif.     (city :wiki "Los_Angeles" :name (name :op1 "LA") :location (state :wiki "California" :name (name :op1 "Calif.")))    Example

             
      Example: USC Prof. Z. Meyer lives in LA, Calif. [isi_0002.692]
      (l / live-01
           :ARG0 (p / person

                               :op1 "USC"))

           :location (c / city
                :wiki "Los_Angeles"
                :name (n3 / name
                     :op1 "LA")

                     :wiki "California"
                     :name (n4 / name
                          :op1 "Calif."))))
  • Specific abbreviations
    • DD   dear daughter
    • DH   dear husband
    • DS   dear son

    • OP   original poster
  • related topic spelling standard   (American English)
  • related topic alternate form   ("80 kilometers or 50 miles")
  • related topic :wiki   (wikification)

adverb   (ID)
  • Most adverbs ending in -ly are mapped to their core concepts.
    • The boy sang very beautifully.     (sing-01 :ARG0 boy :ARG1-of beautiful-02)    Example

             
      Example: The boy sang very beautifully. [isi_0002.35]
      (s / sing-01
           :ARG0 (b / boy)
           :ARG1-of (b2 / beautiful-02
                :degree (v / very)))
    • Carthage was utterly destroyed.     (destroy-01 :ARG1 Carthage :ARG1-of utter-02)    Example

             
      Example: Carthage was utterly destroyed. [isi_0002.201]
      (d / destroy-01
           :ARG1 (c / city
                :wiki "Carthage"
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "Carthage"))
           :ARG1-of (u / utter-02))
    • recently discovered animals     (animal :ARG1-of (discover-01 :time recent))    Example

             
      Example: recently discovered animals [isi_0002.525]
      (a / animal
           :ARG1-of (d / discover-01
                :time (r / recent)))
    • Do you really think so?   [really = in actual fact = real, in this case]     (think :ARG0 you :ARG1 so :ARG1-of real-04)    Example

             
      Example: Do you really think so? [isi_0002.527]
      (t / think-01
           :polarity (a / amr-unknown)
           :ARG0 (y / you)
           :ARG1 (s / so)
           :ARG1-of (r / real-04))
    • He truly believes that he is invincible.   [truly = in actual fact = it is really true that ..., in this case]   (ID)     (believe-01 :ARG0 he :ARG1 invincible :ARG1-of true-01)    Example

             
      Example: He truly believes that he is invincible. [isi_0002.719]
      (b / believe-01
           :ARG0 (h / he)
           :ARG1 (i / invincible
                :domain h)
           :ARG1-of (t / true-01))
    • behaviorally modern humans     (human :ARG0-of (behave-01 :manner modern))    Example

             
      Example: behaviorally modern humans [isi_0002.526]
      (h / human
           :ARG0-of (b / behave-01
                :ARG1-of (m / modern-02)))
  • Exception: -ly is kept if the word has a substantially distinct meaning.
    • He could hardly breathe.   [hardly ≠ hard]     (possible-01 :degree hardly :ARG1 breathe-01)    Example

             
      Example: He could hardly breathe. [isi_0002.522]
      (p / possible-01
           :degree (h / hardly)
           :ARG1 (b / breathe-01
                :ARG0 (h2 / he)))

                :op1 300))
  • Exceptions include words where -ly is part of the core concept:     early, holy, only
  • Exceptions include adjectives where the -ly adds to the meaning of the underlying noun such as:     costly, friendly, lonely, lovely, timely
  • Exceptions include adverbs that don't have a clear mapping:     accordingly
  • Exception: kindly can be expressed as :polite +

amr-empty   (ID)
  • usage
    • To annotate 'sentences' that contain no meaning, e.g. an empty string or some punctuation and function words. In the AMR corpus, such 'degenerate' sentences typically result from incorrect sentence segmentation, e.g. when the string 'READ. The. Previous. Post. In. The. Thread.' was segmented into 7 'sentences' by an automatic tool and then made it into the corpus without human detection and correction. However, such cases are rare.
  • punctuation
    • .   [a lone period]     (amr-empty)    Example

             
      Example: . [isi_0002.795]
      (a / amr-empty)
  • function word
    • the     (amr-empty)    Example

             
      Example: the [isi_0002.796]
      (a / amr-empty)
  • disfluency
    • uh     (amr-empty)    Example

             
      Example: uh [isi_0002.798]
      (a / amr-empty)

                     :ARG2 (t / this))))
    • :value "..." captures unintelligible string
  • ... despite best efforts.
    • Please use amr-unintelligible only as a last resort, after having looked at a wide context and having performed a web search.

  • related topic adverb

argument raising   (ID)
  • definition
    • Argument raising (or just raising) is a construction where a given predicate takes a dependent that is not its semantic argument, but rather is the semantic argument of an embedded predicate. In AMR, the raised argument has to be lowered back to the predicate to which it semantically belongs.
  • examples
    • The fugitive is believed to hide in Pakistan. [= It is believed that the fugitive hides in Pakistan.]     (believe-01 :ARG1 (hide-01 :ARG0 fugitive :location Pakistan))    Example

             
      Example: The fugitive is believed to hide in Pakistan. [isi_0002.641]
      (b / believe-01
           :ARG1 (h / hide-01
                :ARG0 (f / fugitive)
                :location (c / country
                     :wiki "Pakistan"
                     :name (n / name
                          :op1 "Pakistan"))))
    • The software is intended to increase productivity.     (intend-01 :ARG1 (increase-01 :ARG0 software :ARG1 productivity))    Example

             
      Example: The software is intended to increase productivity. [isi_0002.640]
      (i / intend-01
           :ARG1 (i2 / increase-01
                :ARG0 (s / software)
                :ARG1 (p / productive-03)))
    • Bill Gates is known to be rich.     (know-01 :ARG1 (rich :domain Bill Gates))    Example

             
      Example: Bill Gates is known to be rich. [isi_0002.642]
      (k / know-01
           :ARG1 (r / rich
                :domain (p / person
                     :wiki "Bill_Gates"
                     :name (n / name
                          :op1 "Bill"
                          :op2 "Gates"))))
    • I know Bill Gates to be rich.     (know-01 :ARG0 I :ARG1 (rich :domain Bill Gates))    Example

             
      Example: I know that Bill Gates is rich. [isi_0002.632]
      (k / know-01

    • I oppose weapons intended for killing other humans.     (oppose-01 :ARG0 I :ARG1 (weapon :ARG2-of (kill-01 :ARG1 human :ARG1-of intend-01)))    Example

binding-affinity-91   (ID)   in bio domain, measure of strength of bond between molecules
  • Typical usage context
    • bind-01 :ARG4 binding-affinity-91
  • binding-affinity-91 arguments
    • :ARG1 binding affinity constant measured, e.g. dissociation-constant (Kd), inhibitor-constant (Ki)
    • :ARG2 binding affinity quantity, e.g. concentration-quantity such as 5 nanomolar
  • dissociation-constant Kd
    • Gefitinib binds wild-type EGFR kinase with Kd = 53.5 nM.     (bind-01 :ARG4 (binding-affinity-91 :ARG1 dissociation-constant :ARG2 concentration-quantity))    Example

             
      Example: Gefitinib binds wild-type EGFR kinase with Kd = 53.5 nM. [isi_0002.785]
      (b / bind-01
           :ARG1 (s / small-molecule
                :wiki "Gefitinib"
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "gefitinib"))
           :ARG2 (k / kinase
                :wiki "Epidermal_growth_factor_receptor"
                :name (n2 / name
                     :op1 "EGFR")
                :mod (w / wild-type))
           :ARG4 (b2 / binding-affinity-91
                :ARG1 (d / dissociation-constant)
                :ARG2 (c / concentration-quantity
                     :quant 53.5
                     :unit (n3 / nanomolar))))
  • inhibitor-constant Ki

  • inverse   (ID)
    • :consist-of is considered a base role, and its inverse is :consist-of-of.
    • Similarly for :prep-on-behalf-of, :prep-out-of, and formerly :instead-of (now superseded by frame instead-of-91).
    • In practice, these inverses are exceedingly rare (zero instances in the 2016 AMR Corpus releases).

contrast-01
  • keywords
    • Contrastive conjunctions such as  but, while, whereas
    • Prepositions such as  in contrast to
    • Adverbials such as  however, on the other hand
  • examples
    • The following sentences share the same AMR:
      • I like classical music, but John likes jazz.
      • I like classical music, whereas John likes jazz.
      • While I like classical music, John likes jazz.
      • I like classical music, in contrast to John who likes jazz.
      • I like classical music. John, however, likes jazz.
      • On the one hand, I like classical music. On the other hand, John likes jazz.
      • My liking of classical music contrasts with John's liking of jazz.
          (contrast-01 :ARG1 I like classical music :ARG2 John likes jazz)    Example

             
      Example: I like classical music, but John likes jazz . [isi_0002.103]
      (c / contrast-01
           :ARG1 (l / like-01
                :ARG0 (i / i)
                :ARG1 (m / music
                     :mod (c2 / classics)))
           :ARG2 (l2 / like-01
                :ARG0 (p / person
                     :wiki -
                     :name (n / name
                          :op1 "John"))
                :ARG1 (j / jazz)))
    • But that's not his fault.     (contrast-01 :ARG2 fault)    Example

             
      Example: But that's not his fault. [isi_0002.368]
      (c / contrast-01
           :ARG2 (f / fault-01
                :polarity -
                :ARG1 (h / he)
                :ARG2 (t / that)))

  • symmetry
    • contrast-01 is symmetric, i.e. the arguments of contrast-01 can typically be swapped without changing the meaning. This can be used as a test to check whether contrast-01 is indeed the proper annotation, as in the following example:
      • I like classical music, whereas John likes jazz.
      • John likes jazz, whereas I like classical music.

    • will flag cycles as an error otherwise

  • have-degree-91 vs. have-quant-91
    • Note that in general, have-degree-91 is used with gradable properties, often expressed as an adjective (taller, less powerful, most totalitarian, etc.) or as an adverb (more quickly, further) whereas have-quant-91 is used with objects, substances, quantities, often expressed as a noun with a quantifier (the most cars, more water, more money, less oversight).
      Nonetheless, there can be some ambiguous overlap between the two. At the most basic level, consider: Is it a property or a quantity under discussion? If uncertain, have-degree-91 is a more general roleset than have-quant-91, so the default should be have-degree-91.
      The following test may be helpful in cases where the potential property/quantity word is ambiguous: the word should be modifiable by 'many' or 'much' if appropriate for have-quant-91; or by 'very' for have-degree-91:
      Sentencemuch/many testvery testProper concept
      The girl is taller than the boy.Bad: The girl is much/many tall.Good: The girl is very tall.have-degree-91
      They supplied at a lower price.Bad: at a much/many low priceGood: at a very low pricehave-degree-91
      The total was far higher than expected.Bad: Total was much/many high.Good: Total was very high.have-degree-91
      He bought as much beer as he could carry.Good: He bought much beer.Bad: He bought very beer.have-quant-91
      The product has far more monetary value on the black market.Good: Product has much monetary value.Bad: Product has very monetary value.have-quant-91
      You have done more to screw this country up than the Democrats.Good: You have done much.Bad: You have done very.have-quant-91

    • Note that some concepts such as "high" can be :degree intensifiers in some contexts (e.g. I highly recommend that dentist. and The chemical is highly stable.), but not in others (e.g. high speed or The mountain is very high.). One test to determine whether something is an intensifier is to see whether it can naturally be replaced by the common intensifiers very or very much.   (ID)

 disputed and tricky GPEs
  • country   (includes countries that are defunct or have only partial (but still significant) characteristics of a country)
    • Countries include: England, Kosovo, Northern Ireland, Palestine, Scotland, Soviet Union, Taiwan, Wales, Yugoslavia
  • state   (subdivision of a country with high degree of federalism)
    • States include: states of Germany, India, United States; regions of Spain
  • province
    • Provinces include: provinces of Canada, provinces and autonomous regions of China, departements of France, prefectures of Japan, oblasts of Russia
  • city   (includes villages and towns)
    • Cities include: Hong Kong, Washington, D.C.
  • Bosnia and Herzegovina
    • Bosnia and Herzegovina is a single country, not two countries. Part of former Yugoslavia until 1992.
    • spelling variation: Bosnia and Herzegowina, Bosnia-Herzegovina, sometimes just Bosnia for short
  • Chechnya   (demonym: Chechen)
    • Only temporarily by-and-large de facto independent from Russia in the late 1990s. Annotate as "province".
  • French Guiana
    • French Guiana is a départment of France, not a separate country. Annotate as "province".
  • Gibraltar
    • Gibraltar is a British Overseas Territory, not a separate country. Annotate as "territory".
  • Kashmir
    • Generally annotated as world-region, unless the text explicitly refers to a part of Kashmir exclusively administered by India or Pakistan, in which case the entity should be annotated as state, province or country-region according to the specific text.
  • Serbia and Montenegro
    • During the process of Yugoslav disintegration, Serbia and Montenegro was a single country from 1992-2006, before splitting into two separate countries: (1) Serbia and (2) Montenegro.

distribution-range-91   (ID)   typically used for normal distributions with mean and standard deviation
  • frame arguments
    • :ARG1 center, mean
    • :ARG2 lower bound
    • :ARG3 upper bound
    • :ARG4 radius, distance from center to bounds
    • :ARG5 confidence that value is in range, typically a percentage, e.g. 95%
    • :ARG6 deviation covered by range, e.g. standard-deviation, standard-error-of-the-mean
    • :ARG7 type of distribution, e.g. normal-distribution
  • examples

:domain   (ID)

    • This role is used in constructions such as ... is <noun> and ... is <adjective> when there is no frame for that noun or adjective:
    • Note that the property of an entity is annotated as the head concept.

  • extraposition of subject clauses   (ID)   (That annotators recognize extrapositions   is   important.)
    • What is it?   When an underlying sentence is of the type "A is B." and the subject A is a verbal clause and B is short, people often extrapose the subject and say "It is B that A." or something similar. It is important that annotators recognize such an extraposition and preserve B as the semantic head and A as the :domain.
    • It's important to be polite.   [= To be polite is important.]     (important-01 :ARG1 polite-01)    Example

             
      Example: It's important to be polite. [isi_0002.783]
      (i / important-01
           :ARG1 (p / polite-01))
    • Difficult to believe that John speaks 5 languages.   [= To believe that John speaks 5 languages is difficult.]     (difficult :domain believe-01)    Example

             
      Example: Difficult to believe that John speaks 5 languages. [isi_0002.784]
      (d / difficult
           :domain (b / believe-01
                :ARG1 (s / speak-01
                     :ARG0 (p / person
                          :wiki -
                          :name (n / name
                               :op1 "John"))
                     :ARG3 (l / language
                          :quant 5))))
    • It is a problem that glaciers are melting.   [= That glaciers are melting is a problem.]     (problem :domain melt-01)    Example

             
      Example: It is a problem that glaciers are melting. [isi_0002.476]
      (p / problem
           :domain (m / melt-01
                :ARG1 (g / glacier)))
    • The problem is glaciers are melting.   [= That glaciers are melting is the problem.]     (problem :domain melt-01)    Example

             
      Example: The problem is glaciers are melting. [isi_0002.477]
      (p / problem
           :domain (m / melt-01
                :ARG1 (g / glacier)))
    • But:   That was a long flight.   [Sometimes, the head of :domain is an event.]     (fly-01 :domain that)    Example

             
      Example: That was a long flight. [isi_0002.478]
      (f / fly-01
           :ARG1-of (l / long-03)
           :domain (t / that))
    • Typical AMR Checker warning:   Warning: unusual role :domain under recognize-01
  • However, as a reminder, please use frames as available:

 exclamation   (ID)
  • :mode expressive   (used to mark interjections such as ah, ha, hmm, oh, wow, yippee that express emotions)
    • Wow!     (wow :mode expressive)    Example

             
      Example: Wow! [isi_0002.196]
      (w / wow
           :mode expressive)
    • Yippee!     (yippee :mode expressive)    Example

             
      Example: Yippee! [isi_0002.197]
      (y / yippee
           :mode expressive)
    • Yes!!!   (ID)     (yes :mode expressive)    Example

             
      Example: Yes!!! [isi_0002.657]
      (y / yes
           :mode expressive)
    • Note that "Yes." as a normal answer to a question is not marked with any :mode, as it plainly conveys information based on the preceding question. But a celebratory "Yes!!!" after your favorite sports team scores an imporant point should be marked up using :mode expressive.
    • Do not use :mode expressive merely to convey emphasis (e.g. ALLCAPS), an exclamation mark (!) or a disfluency (e.g. uh), all of which are not annotated in AMR.   (ID)
  • related topic :mode

  • frame arguments
    • :ARG0 office holder
    • :ARG1 organization
    • :ARG2 role or title of office held
    • :ARG3 description of responsibility (used only occasionally)

  • When to use have-org-role-91
    • if the role clearly implies an organization, even if neither organization nor name of officeholder are mentioned explicitly   (e.g. ambassador, archbishop, bishop, CEO, chairman, chancellor, chief of staff, commissioner, congressman, deputy, dictator, director, emperor, empress, envoy, foreign minister, governor, head-of-state, king, mayor, monarch, officer, official, pope, premier, president, prime minister, principal, professor, queen, secretary, senator, spokesman, spokeswoman, treasurer etc.)
    • member of a political party ("Democrat", "Republican")
    • member of a legislative body ("senator", "MP")
    • military ranks ("general", "colonel")
    • capital (or financial center, main city) of a GPE   (ID)
  • When not to use have-org-role-91
    • when there is another explicit verb frame such as employ-01, serve-01, head-01, lead-02 [exception: multi-word concept head-of-state is ok as :ARG2 of have-org-role-91]
    • organization-independent occupation/skill: lawyer, teacher, reporter (unless an organization is explicitly mentioned and person is employee/member of organization, as opposed to an outside freelancer such as a lawyer retained for a specific case)
  • shortcuts
    • :role     (person :role president) => (person :ARG0-of (have-org-role-91 :ARG2 president))
    • :employed-by     (person :employed-by company) => (person :ARG0-of (have-org-role-91 :ARG1 company))

      Example: John and Mary are husband and wife. [isi_0002.440]
      (h / have-rel-role-91
           :ARG0 (p / person
                :wiki -
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "John"))
           :ARG1 (p2 / person
                :wiki -
                :name (n2 / name
                     :op1 "Mary"))
           :ARG2 (h2 / husband)
           :ARG3 (w / wife))

      Entity typesdifferent
      e.g. person/organization      		same
      e.g. person/person
      No. of roles1
      e.g. president      		2   (a pair)
      e.g. mother/son
      (2nd role often only implied)

have-rel-role-91   (ID)   have relational role, e.g. father/son
  • frame arguments
    • :ARG0 entity A
    • :ARG1 entity B (typically of same type)
    • :ARG2 role of entity A
    • :ARG3 role of entity B (often left unspecified but implied)
    • :ARG4 case or contract (rare)

  • When to use have-rel-role-91   (ID)
    • family relationships   (e.g. ancestor, aunt, bro, brother, brother-in-law, child (in parent/child relational sense), cousin, dad, daughter, daughter-in-law, descendant, father, father-in-law, godchild, goddaughter, godfather, godmother, godparent, godson, grandchild, granddaughter, grandfather, grandmother, grandparent, grandson, husband, in-law (as in "my in-laws"), kid (in parent/child relational sense), mom, mother, mother-in-law, mum, mummy, nephew, niece, parent, pop, relative, sibling, sister, sister-in-law, son, son-in-law, spouse, stepbrother, stepchild, stepdaughter, stepfather, stepmother, stepsister, stepson, uncle, wife)
    • professional relationships   (e.g. landlord,landlady/tenant, lawyer/client, boss, doctor, general practioner, therapist, patient) in the relational sense of "my lawyer", "my doctor"
    • friend, boyfriend, girlfriend, significant-other, partner (in the sense of significant-other), best-man, buddy, comrade, housemate, maid-of-honor, mate, peer (in the relational sense), roommate, running-mate, shipmate; enemy
    • sister city, twin town
  • When not to use have-rel-role-91
    • when there is another explicit verb frame such as employ-01, teach-01
    • when there is (or should be) another explicit event noun frame such as crime-01, surgery-01 (criminal/victim, surgeon/patient)
    • child in the sense of "young person"
    • partner in the sense of business partner, political partner, or partner on a project (partner-01)
    • China is an important trading partner of the United States.   (ID)     (partner-01 :ARG0 China :ARG1 United States :purpose trade-01 :ARG1-of important-01)    Example

             
      Example: China is an important trading partner of the United States. [isi_0002.472]

           :ARG0 (c / country
                :wiki "China"
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "China"))
           :ARG1 (c2 / country
                :wiki "United_States"

                     :op1 "United"
                     :op2 "States"))
           :purpose (t / trade-01)
           :ARG1-of (i / important-01))
  • shortcuts
    • :role     (person :role mother) => (person :ARG0-of (have-rel-role-91 :ARG2 mother))

implied argument   (ID)
  • overview
    • Some entities play multiple roles in a sentence. Some of those roles played by an entity are indicated by a pronoun ("he/him/his"), a to-clause ("He wanted to win."), or even nothing at all. All these roles must be annotated if they are clearly implied by the sentence.
  • examples
    • The boy wants to be kissed.     (want-01 :ARG0 (b / boy) :ARG1 (kiss-01 :ARG1 b))    Example

             
      Example: The boy wants to be kissed. [isi_0002.552]
      (w / want-01
           :ARG0 (b / boy)
           :ARG1 (k / kiss-01
                :ARG1 b))
    • In the sentence above, the boy plays two roles, as both the logical subject (:ARG0) of want and the logical object (:ARG1) of kiss.
    • U.S. president Roosevelt announced his decision to run for reelection.    
      (announce :ARG0 (p / person :wiki "Franklin_D._Roosevelt")
                :ARG1 (decide :ARG0 p :ARG1 (run-02 :ARG0 p :ARG1 (reelect-01 :ARG1 p))))          Example

             
      Example: U.S. president Roosevelt announced his decision to run for reelection. [isi_0002.447]
      (a / announce-01
           :ARG0 (p / person
                :wiki "Franklin_D._Roosevelt"
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "Roosevelt")
                :ARG0-of (h / have-org-role-91
                     :ARG1 (c / country
                          :wiki "United_States"
                          :name (n2 / name
                               :op1 "U.S."))
                     :ARG2 (p2 / president)))
           :ARG1 (d / decide-01
                :ARG0 p
                :ARG1 (r / run-02
                     :ARG0 p
                     :ARG1 (r2 / reelect-01
                          :ARG1 p))))
    • In the sentence above, Roosevelt plays four roles, as the announcer, the decider, the runner and the reelectee. This is reflected in four occurrences of the variable p.

implied relation   Most implied relations are expressed as roles, but occasionally, we "hallucinate" concepts such as cost-01 or say-01. (See end of this entry.)

      (b / bathe-01
           :ARG0 (b2 / boy))
  • Light verb construction or not?
    • Positive example: I've arranged for you to have a look at his file in our library. (= I've arranged for you to look at his file in our library.)     This is a light verb construction.
    • Negative example: He had a look of childish bewilderment on his face. (had a look cannot be replaced by looked).     So this is not a light verb construction.
  • List of common light verb constructions
    • Click here for a common list of mappings from light verb construction to AMR concept.
    • Any unmapped light verb constructions in the list above will be flagged by the AMR Checker.

multi-sentence
  • When a sentence is really multiple sentences, use multi-sentence as a top, and :snt1, :snt2 etc. as roles.
  • I came. I saw. I conquered.     (multi-sentence :snt1 come-01 :snt2 see-01 :snt3 conquer-01)    Example

           
    Example: I came. I saw. I conquered. [isi_0002.109]
    (m / multi-sentence
         :snt1 (c / come-01
              :ARG1 (i / i))
         :snt2 (s / see-01
              :ARG0 (i2 / i))
         :snt3 (c2 / conquer-01
              :ARG0 (i3 / i)))
  • Note: In AMR 1.2, the individual (sub-) sentences are still annotated independently, i.e. without sharing co-reference variables. In the example above, for example, the "I" does not have a shared co-reference variable, even though all three instances of "I" refer to the same person (Julius Caesar).

    • Annotating names in AMR   [2 minutes]
  • shortcut
    • The AMR Editor will automatically expand editor commands such as
      x :ARG0 person Michael Bloomberg
          to a sequence that will effectively build
      x :ARG0 (p / person :name (n / name :op1 "Michael" :op2 "Bloomberg"))

  • transferred negation, also referred to as negative raising   (ID)   (syntactic structure ≠ semantic structure)
    • The boy doesn't think the Yankees will win.   [= The boy thinks that the Yankees will not win.]     (think-01 :ARG0 boy :ARG1 (win-01 :polarity - :ARG0 Yankees))    Example

             
      Example: The boy does n't think the Yankees will win. [isi_0001.12]
      (t / think-01
           :ARG0 (b / boy)
           :ARG1 (w / win-01
                :polarity -
                :ARG0 (t2 / team
                     :wiki "New_York_Yankees"
                     :name (n / name
                          :op1 "Yankees"))))
    • It doesn't appear it will rain tomorrow.   [= It appears it will not rain tomorrow.]     (appear-02 :ARG1 (rain-01 :polarity - :time tomorrow))    Example

             
      Example: It doesn't appear it will rain tomorrow. [isi_0002.628]
      (a / appear-02
           :ARG1 (r / rain-01
                :polarity -
                :time (t / tomorrow)))
    • I don't want to leave.   [= I want to not leave. = I want to stay.]     (want-01 :ARG0 i :ARG1 (leave-01 :polarity - :ARG0 i))    Example

             
      Example: I don't want to leave. [isi_0002.629]
      (w / want-01
           :ARG0 (i / i)
           :ARG1 (l / leave-11
                :polarity -
                :ARG0 i))
    • For matrix clauses with certain verbs of opinion or perception, the negative form in a subordinate clause can be transferred to the matrix clause, especially in informal texts. In these cases, the AMR annotation attaches :polarity - to the subordinate clause level where it semantically belongs, even if it is syntactically expressed at the matrix clause level.   [See examples above.]
    • Verbs that allow transferred negation include verbs of opinion: anticipate, be supposed to, believe, calculate, expect, figure, imagine, reckon, suppose, think,   verbs of perception: appear, seem; feel/look/sound as-if/like   and other verbs: want, wish.
    • Note that for these verbs, any negation of a matrix verb might have resulted from transferred negation, but the negation might also semantically belong to the matrix verb. The annotator will have to resolve this ambiguity on a case-by-case basis using context.
  • don't like vs. dislike   (ID)

pragmatics   (ID)
  • overview
    • Sometimes, the true meaning of a sentence is not what it seems to be superficially. For example, a question might really be a polite command.
    • AMR captures the intended sense.
  • question as polite command
    • Could you close the door?   [syntactically a question, pragmatically a command: Close the door, please!]     (close-01 :mode imperative :polite +)    Example

             
      Example: Could you close the door? [isi_0002.297]
      (c / close-01
           :mode imperative
           :polite +
           :ARG0 (y / you)
           :ARG1 (d / door))
  • polite indirect question
    • Could you tell me what time it is?   [= What time is it?]     (date-entity :polite + :time amr-unknown)    Example

             
      Example: Could you tell me what time it is? [isi_0002.301]
      (d / date-entity
           :polite +
           :time (a / amr-unknown))
  • argument raising
    • The boy doesn't think the Yankees will win.   [= The boy thinks that the Yankees will not win.]     (think-01 :ARG0 boy :ARG1 (win-01 :polarity - :ARG0 Yankees))    Example

             
      Example: The boy does n't think the Yankees will win. [isi_0001.12]
      (t / think-01
           :ARG0 (b / boy)
           :ARG1 (w / win-01
                :polarity -
                :ARG0 (t2 / team
                     :wiki "New_York_Yankees"
                     :name (n / name
                          :op1 "Yankees"))))
    • I don't want to leave.   [= I want to not leave. = I want to stay.]     (want-01 :ARG0 i :ARG1 (leave-01 :polarity - :ARG0 i))    Example

             
      Example: I don't want to leave. [isi_0002.629]
      (w / want-01
           :ARG0 (i / i)
           :ARG1 (l / leave-11
                :polarity -
                :ARG0 i))
  • conditional relevance
    • My name is Bill if you need me.   [In sentences like these, My name is Bill no matter what, even if you don't need me, but it will be relevant to you if you need me.]     (name-01 :ARG1 I :ARG2 Bill :ARG1-of (relevant-01 :ARG2 you :condition need-01))    Example

             
      Example: My name is Bill if you need me. [isi_0002.814]
      (n / name-01
           :ARG1 (i / i)

                :name (n2 / name
                     :op1 "Bill"))

                :ARG2 (y / you)
                :condition (n3 / need-01
                     :ARG0 y
                     :ARG1 i)))

                :ARG0 (i / i)
                :ARG1 (m / money
                     :mod (m2 / more)))
           :ARG2 (p / person
                :ARG0-of (h / have-rel-role-91
                     :ARG1 i
                     :ARG2 (f / father))))

preposition   (ID)
  • specific prepositions
    • See the individual listing for each preposition.
    • Check for precedents using the AMR Editor's "search" button.
  • How to eliminate :prep-X roles.
    • Use the frame's :ARGx or use a general purpose role.    
      (defend-01 :prep-with gun) → (defend-01 :ARG2 gun)
      (defend-01 :prep-with courage) → (defend-01 :manner courageous)
    • Is the preposition part of a multiword expression?
      Check for precedents in the multiword expression section of a specific preposition or by using the AMR Editor's "search" button.    
      (know-01 :prep-of course) → (know-01 :mod of-course)
      (solve-01 :prep-by myself) → (solve-01 :mod by-oneself)
    • Try to rephrase by mapping to a verb that captures the same meaning.    
      (invisible :prep-to eye) → (possible-01 :polarity - :ARG1 (see-01 :instrument eye))
    • Cases where :prep-X can't be avoided yet:  missing frame   (AMR to be updated when frame eventually becomes available.)    
      (consistent :prep-with Y :domain X)   no frame for: "X is consistent with Y"
      (in-step :prep-with Y :domain X)   no frame for: "X is in-step with Y"
  • external resources
    • PrepWiki at CMU (primarily for AMR guideline developers)

pronoun   (ID)
  • Examples of pronouns
    • subject pronouns: I, you, he, she, it, we, they
    • object pronouns: me, you, him, her, it, us, them
    • possessive pronouns: my, your, his, her, its, our, their
    • reflexive pronouns: myself, yourself, himself, herself, itself, ourselves, yourselves, themselves
    • independent pronouns: mine, yours, his, hers, its, ours, theirs
    • demonstrative pronouns: this, these, that, those     ("I like that.")
    • relative pronouns: who, whom, which, that     (the girl who adjusted the machine)
    • other pronouns: so     ("I can't believe she left but he said so.")
  • Pronoun refers to another entity in the sentence.
    • The boy lost his toy.     (lose-02 :ARG0 (b / boy) :ARG1 (toy :poss b))    Example

             
      Example: The boy lost his toy. [isi_0002.205]
      (l / lose-02
           :ARG0 (b / boy)
           :ARG1 (t / toy
                :poss b))
    • When he opened his eyes, John saw himself in the mirror.    
      (see-01 :ARG0 (p / person :name (name :op1 "John")) :ARG1 p
              :time (open-01 :ARG0 p :ARG1 (eye :part-of p)))          Example

             
      Example: When he opened his eyes, John saw himself in the mirror. [isi_0002.207]
      (s / see-01
           :ARG0 (p / person
                :wiki -
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "John"))
           :ARG1 p
           :location (m / mirror)
           :time (o / open-01
                :ARG0 p
                :ARG1 (e / eye
                     :part-of p)))

publication-91   (ID)
  • frame arguments
    • :ARG0 author(s)
    • :ARG1 title
    • :ARG2 abstract
    • :ARG3 full text
    • :ARG4 venue (journal, conference)
    • :ARG5 volume
    • :ARG6 issue
    • :ARG7 pages
    • :ARG8 ID(s), e.g. PubMed
    • :ARG9 editor(s)
  • in scientific publications
    • Albert Einstein: Zur Elektrodynamik bewegter Körper (1905) Annalen der Physik, 322 (10): 891-921 (in German)     (publication-91 :ARG0 Einstein :ARG1 Zur ... :time 1905 :medium German)    Example

             
      Example: Albert Einstein: Zur Elektrodynamik bewegter Körper (1905) Annalen der Physik, 322 (10): 891-921 (in German) [isi_0002.561]
      (p / publication-91
           :ARG5 "322"
           :ARG6 "10"

                :wiki "Albert_Einstein"
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "Albert"
                     :op2 "Einstein"))
           :ARG1 (p3 / publication
                :wiki "Annus_Mirabilis_papers#Special_relativity"
                :name (n2 / name
                     :op1 "Zur"
                     :op2 "Elektrodynamik"
                     :op3 "bewegter"
                     :op4 "Körper"))
           :ARG4 (j / journal
                :wiki "Annalen_der_Physik"
                :name (n3 / name
                     :op1 "Annalen"
                     :op2 "der"
                     :op3 "Physik"))
           :ARG7 (v / value-interval
                :op1 891
                :op2 921)
           :time (d / date-entity
                :year 1905)
           :medium (l / language
                :wiki "German_language"
                :name (n4 / name
                     :op1 "German")))
    • Michel Galley, Mark Hopkins, Kevin Knight and Daniel Marcu: What's in a Translation Rule? HLT-NAACL 2004, pp. 273-280     (publication-91 :ARG0 (and ...) :ARG4 HLT-NAACL :time 2004)    Example

punctuation   (ID)
  • AMR generally does not represent punctuation.
    • It started to rain; however, the game continued.     Example

             
      Example: It started to rain; however, the game continued . [isi_0002.183]
      (s / start-01
           :ARG1 (r / rain-01)
           :concession-of (c / continue-01
                :ARG1 (g / game)))
  • exceptions
    • Punctuation that is part of a name:
          The poet William Shakespeare was born in Stratford-upon-Avon.     (city :name (name :op1 "Stratford-upon-Avon"))    Example

             
      Example: The poet William Shakespeare was born in Stratford-upon-Avon. [isi_0002.209]
      (b / bear-02
           :ARG1 (p / poet
                :wiki "William_Shakespeare"
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "William"
                     :op2 "Shakespeare"))
           :location (c / city
                :wiki "Stratford-upon-Avon"
                :name (n2 / name
                     :op1 "Stratford-upon-Avon")))
    • Punctuation that is part of an email address:
          [email protected]     (email-address-entity :value "[email protected]")    Example

             
      Example: [email protected] [isi_0002.11]
      (e / email-address-entity
           :value "[email protected]")
    • Punctuation that is part of a URL:
          www.whitehouse.gov     (url-entity :value "www.whitehouse.gov")    Example

             
      Example: www.whitehouse.gov [isi_0002.12]
      (u / url-entity
           :value "www.whitehouse.gov")
  • $   (dollar sign)
    • a $3 meal     (meal :cost (monetary-quantity :quant 3 :unit dollar))    Example

             
      Example: a $3 meal [isi_0002.190]
      (m / meal
           :ARG1-of (c / cost-01
                :ARG2 (m2 / monetary-quantity
                     :quant 3

    • Do NOT use amr-unknown for nominal relative clauses/embedded wh-clauses, even if there are unknowns in the sentence. amr-unknown is reserved for direct questions that request an answer and have (or should have) a question mark for the full sentence.

rate-entity-91
  • frame arguments
    • :ARG1 quantity (with an implied default of 1)
    • :ARG2 per quantity
    • :ARG3 regular interval between events   (more specific than :ARG2)
    • :ARG4 entity on which recurring event happens
  • common pattern for recurring events
    • (event  :frequency  rate-entity-91)
  • examples
    • twice a year     (rate-entity-91 :ARG1 2 :ARG2 (temporal-quantity :quant 1 :unit year))    Example

             
      Example: twice a year [isi_0002.274]
      (r / rate-entity-91
           :ARG1 "2"
           :ARG2 (t / temporal-quantity
                :quant 1
                :unit (y / year)))
    • I have to renew my car insurance every six months.     (rate-entity-91 :ARG3 (temporal-quantity :quant 6 :unit month))    Example

                          :quant 6
                          :unit (m / month)))))

    • Keywords:
      • once, twice, n times

      • hourly, daily, weekly, monthly, quarterly, yearly, annual, annually;   biweekly, bimonthly, semiannual, semiannually, biannual, biannually

reification   (in AMR Guidelines on github, includes full examples)
  • Definition: Conversion of a role into a concept.
  • Purpose: Allows reified concept to connect to more than 2 concepts, or to be at the top of the AMR.
  • Example: :location → be-located-at-91
  • Example: :purpose → have-purpose-91
  • List of reifications

:scale   (ID)
  • usage
    • :scale  is used in quantities (such as temperature-quantity and seismic-quantity) where a  :quant 0  does not represent a 0-quantity.
      :scale  takes the place of  :unit  in other quantities.
  • temperature-quantity
    • She heated the oven to 250 degrees Celsius.     (temperature-quantity :quant 250 :scale celsius)    Example

             
      Example: She heated the oven to 250 degrees Celsius. [isi_0002.33]
      (h / heat-01
           :ARG0 (s / she)
           :ARG1 (o / oven)
           :destination (t / temperature-quantity
                :quant 250
                :scale (c / celsius)))
  • seismic-quantity
    • 7.9 on the Richter scale     Example

      (s / seismic-quantity
           :quant 7.9

 shortcuts
  • What are shortcuts?
    • Non-re-ified roles for easier annotation. The AMR Editor automatically expands shortcut role constructions to their proper canonical form.
      For shortcut roles such as :cause, the editor also supports inverse shortcut roles such as :cause-of.
  • cause-01
    • Shortcut role:   :cause     (tsunami :cause earthquake) => (tsunami :ARG1-of (cause-01 :ARG0 earthquake))
  • cite-01
    • Shortcut role:   :cite     (publication :cite "Einstein, 1905") => (publication :ARG1-of (cite-01 :ARG2 "Einstein, 1905"))
  • cost-01
    • Shortcut role:   :cost     (product :cost monetary-quantity) => (product :ARG1-of (cost-01 :ARG2 monetary-quantity))
  • except-01
    • Shortcut role:   :except     (country :except Cuba) => (country :ARG2-of (except-01 :ARG1 Cuba))
  • mean-01
    • Shortcut role:   :meaning     (flame :meaning hostile-email) => (flame :ARG1-of (mean-01 :ARG2 hostile-email))
  • have-org-role-91
    • Shortcut role:   :role     (person :role president) => (person :ARG0-of (have-org-role-91 :ARG2 president))
    • Shortcut role:   :employed-by     (person :employed-by company) => (person :ARG0-of (have-org-role-91 :ARG1 company))
  • have-rel-role-91
    • Shortcut role:   :role     (person :role mother) => (person :ARG0-of (have-rel-role-91 :ARG2 mother))
  • include-91
    • Shortcut role:   :subset     (large-set :subset small-set) => (large-set :ARG2-of (include-91 :ARG1 small-set))
    • Shortcut role:   :superset     (small-set :superset large-set) => (small-set :ARG1-of (include-91 :ARG2 large-set))
  • instead-of-91
    • Shortcut role:   :instead-of     (give :instead-of take) => (give :ARG1-of (instead-of-91 :ARG2 take))
  • see also shortcuts under
    • named entity
    • ordinal

so   (ID)
  • :degree
    • You are so beautiful!     (beautiful :degree so :domain you)    Example

             
      Example: You are so beautiful! [isi_0002.532]

spelling standard   (ID)
  • AMR spelling standard: American English
    • The aluminium centre organised an aeroplane programme.     (organize-01 :ARG0 (center :topic aluminum) :ARG1 (program :topic airplane))    Example

             
      Example: The aluminium centre organised an aeroplane programme. [isi_0002.690]
      (o / organize-01
           :ARG0 (c / center
                :topic (a / aluminum))
           :ARG1 (p / program
                :topic (a2 / airplane)))
  • typo   (ID)
    • Typos are corrected as a good copy editor would correct them, including capitalization. Examples:
      • mispell → misspell
      • reciept → receipt
      • Marocco → Morroco
      • U.S. Suppreme court → U.S. Supreme Court
      • Washington county → Washington County
      • home depot (company) → Home Depot
      • second amendment (of the U.S. Constitution) → Second Amendment
          "The U.S. Suppreme court examined the second amendment."    Example

             
      Example: The U.S. Suppreme court examined the second amendment. [isi_0002.754]
      (e / examine-01
           :ARG0 (g / government-organization
                :wiki "Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States"
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "U.S."
                     :op2 "Supreme"
                     :op3 "Court"))
           :ARG1 (l / law
                :wiki "Second_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution"
                :name (n2 / name
                     :op1 "Second"
                     :op2 "Amendment")))
    • Spelling correction can be quite radical, particularly for names (incorrectly) transliterated to English from Chinese and other languages with non-Latin scripts, e.g. Gerlaridy → Gorazde.
    • But do not normalize legitimate variants of a name such as "US", "U.S.", "USA", "United States", "United States of America", "America" or "JFK", "Jack Kennedy", "John F. Kennedy", "John Fitzgerald Kennedy". But these name variants will share the same wikification ("United_States", "John_F._Kennedy").
    • In some cases, particulary when the original name is from a non-Latin script, there are multiple common spellings. Preserve any such common form in AMR. Examples:
      • Gaddafi (Wikipedia), Qadhafi (U.S. State Department), Qaddafi (New York Times)
      • Rachmaninoff, Rachmaninov
          (person :wiki Muammar_Gaddafi :name (name :op1 "Muammar" :op2 "Qaddafi"))    Example

             
      Example: Muammar Qaddafi was killed in 2011. [isi_0002.753]
      (k / kill-01
           :ARG1 (p / person
                :wiki "Muammar_Gaddafi"
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "Muammar"
                     :op2 "Qaddafi"))
           :time (d / date-entity
                :year 2011))
    • Preserve intentional official non-standard spellings of names. Examples:
      • Boston Red Sox (not Red Socks)
      • Kellogg's Froot Loops (not Fruit Loops)
      • Apple's iPhone (not Iphone)
    • This includes official non-American spellings of names. Examples:
      • Labour Party (UK) (not Labor Party)
      • HMS Endeavour, Space Shuttle Endeavour (not Endeavor)
          "The Endeavour can be viewed at the California science centre."    Example

             
      Example: The Endeavour can be viewed at the California science centre. [isi_0002.752]
      (p / possible-01
           :ARG1 (v / view-01
                :ARG1 (s / spaceship
                     :wiki "Space_Shuttle_Endeavour"
                     :name (n / name
                          :op1 "Endeavour"))
                :location (m / museum
                     :wiki "California_Science_Center"
                     :name (n2 / name
                          :op1 "California"
                          :op2 "Science"
                          :op3 "Center"))))
    • This also includes satiric spellings of names. Examples:
      • David DuKKKe
      • Di$neyland
    • User names don't need to conform to standard name spelling conventions, e.g. musikdude, peach174, WorldWatcher
  • related topic abbreviation

:wiki   (ID)
  • What is wikification?
    • Wikification "unites" different surface forms of a named entity (such as US, U.S., USA, United States, United States of America) to a common wiki form (such as United_States) according to the English Wikipedia.
  • example
    • western countries (e.g. the UK, the USA and France)     (country :wiki "United_States" :name (name :op1 "USA"))    Example

             
      Example: western countries (e.g. the UK, the USA and France) [isi_0002.413]
      (c / country
           :location (w / world-region
                :wiki "Western_world"
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "West"))
           :example (a / and
                :op1 (c2 / country
                     :wiki "United_Kingdom"
                     :name (n2 / name
                          :op1 "UK"))
                :op2 (c3 / country
                     :wiki "United_States"
                     :name (n3 / name
                          :op1 "USA"))
                :op3 (c4 / country
                     :wiki "France"
                     :name (n4 / name
                          :op1 "France"))))
  • What if a NE is not covered by wikipedia?   (:wiki -)
    • Kevin Knight works at ISI.     (person :wiki - :name (name :op1 "Kevin" :op2 "Knight"))    Example

             
      Example: Kevin Knight works at ISI. [isi_0002.429]
      (w / work-01
           :ARG0 (p / person
                :wiki -
                :name (n / name
                     :op1 "Kevin"
                     :op2 "Knight"))
           :ARG2 (r / research-institute
                :wiki "Information_Sciences_Institute"
                :name (n2 / name
                     :op1 "ISI")))
  • What if I'm not sure how to wikify or if it's not even clear whether something is a named entity or the NE in the AMR is incorrect?   (ID)   (:wiki ?)
    • Wikify questionable NEs with a question mark (:wiki ?).
  • wikification status
    • Release worksets completely wikified as of Nov. 10, 2014
  • AMR Wikification Editor
    • Guidelines: AMR Wikification Editor guidelines   (ID)
    • Examples: wsj100-sent, Little Prince (as of March 10, 2014)
    • Invocation: (1) load the workset you wish to wikify (or correct wikification); (2) click on the blue "wiki" button.
  • canonical form   (ID)
    • Please make sure you use the canonical form of Wikipedia.
    • The wiki page must not be a disambiguation page. Use :wiki "Georgia_(country)" or :wiki "Georgia_(U.S._state)", not :wiki "Georgia".
    • The wiki page must not be a redirection page. Use :wiki "United_States", not :wiki "United_States_of_America"
    • Wikifications use underscores instead of spaces, e.g. :wiki "United_States", not :wiki "United States".
    • Wikifications use UTF8 encodings, e.g. :wiki "Hugo_Chávez", not :wiki "Hugo_Ch%C3%A1vez".
    • Inside a wikification string, represent a double quote (") as the escape sequence "%22", because otherwise it will be confused with the string terminator, e.g. :wiki "Russian_News_Agency_%22TASS%22", not :wiki "Russian_News_Agency_"TASS"".
    • When you use the AMR Wikification Editor, most encoding normalizations will be done automatically.
